          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "President Joe Biden has announced four nominees for the Federal Retirement Thrift Investment Board (FRTIB), the board that oversees the nearly $800 billion federal pension fund. The appointments are significant because these board members will decide how to invest the retirement funds of the nation’s federal employees, including military service members.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Moreover, as ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 2,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "The Daily Poster",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              },
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": " recently reported",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "__GHOST_URL__/biden-is-ignoring-an-easy-climate-victory/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", the current FRTIB board members have so far resisted divesting the pension fund from fossil fuels and shielding it from climate-related financial risks.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Biden had a chance to fill the board with nominees committed to make the retirement plan the largest pension fund in the world to divest from climate risks. But an ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "early look",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://therevolvingdoorproject.org/biden-picks-fintech-speculator-and-morgan-stanley-alum-for-federal-pensions-board/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " at the nominees by the Revolving Door Project, a government watchdog group, suggests that several of Biden’s picks, including a financial technology speculator and a former Morgan Stanley portfolio manager, are going to need to be pressured into divesting the fund.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "“​​We should hope that a President who signed an executive order on greening the financial system would respond appropriately to the [Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]’s dire new report and put his government’s literal money where his mouth is,” the Revolving Door Project wrote in a blog post about the new nominees. “The actual names we’ve gotten, however, are a mixed bag... While some nominees appear to have workers and the planet’s interests at heart, they may have to fend off those looking to use civil servants’ nest eggs as more fuel for their speculative investment engines.”",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
